  "decision_frame": "We must decide how to allocate limited cold-chain DC capacity and expedited inbound inventory to meet a transient ~18% demand spike for berries in the Southwest region over six days, while avoiding excessive stockouts elsewhere or wasting high-cost expedited supply. Key uncertainties: true uplift magnitude (forecast vs realized), duration (6 days +/-), current inbound raspberries arrival timing, and store-level baseline demand given last year’s stockout-censored comps. Objectives (ordered): 1) Protect service in highest-margin / highest-velocity Southwest stores to capture incremental revenue/profit during the spike; 2) Minimize total lost sales across company (reduce stockouts where incremental demand is real); 3) Avoid over-committing DC cold-chain capacity that would displace other critical assortments or cause spoilage; 4) Control incremental transportation and expedite costs. Tradeoffs: committing significant DC capacity to berries increases risk of stockouts for other perishables and raises spoilage/holding costs; under-allocating risks lost revenue and customer dissatisfaction during the heatwave and may miss a short, high-value opportunity; using expedited inbound (air/expedite) mitigates local stockouts but at high cost and limited volume. Constraints: DC has 92% cold capacity already committed; inbound raspberries are 2 days late (adds uncertainty to supply timing); baseline comps are biased low due to 38% stockout censoring last year, so uplift could be understated if customers substituted previously. Time horizon is short (6 days), so decisions must favor nimble reallocation and human oversight.",
  "recommended_allocation": {
    "overall_posture": "conservative-aggressive hybrid: reallocate existing cold-chain capacity to Southwest priority stores where margin and uplift probability are highest, supplement with targeted expedited inbound for top-tier stores only; avoid blanket nationwide reallocation.",
    "allocation_steps": [
      {
        "step": "Identify priority store cohort",
        "action": "Segment Southwest stores by historical berry velocity, margin, and ability to fulfill incremental demand (using non-stockout-censored estimates where possible). Flag top ~20-30% of stores expected to realize highest uplift."
      },
      {
        "step": "Reallocate DC capacity (short-term)",
        "action": "Shift existing committed cold-chain slots toward prioritized Southwest DC-to-store picks by deferring non-critical cold-assortments with low short-term demand. Limit reallocation to the marginal capacity available without exceeding 100% utilization."
      },
      {
        "step": "Targeted expedited inbound",
        "action": "Purchase expedited inbound (air/express) for berries to cover estimated incremental demand only for priority cohort for the 6-day window, capped at a dollar limit tied to expected incremental margin (e.g., expected incremental sales * target margin)."
      },
      {
        "step": "Feed-forward replenishment cadence",
        "action": "Increase delivery frequency to priority stores during the six-day window to smooth on-shelf availability using smaller, more frequent picks from DC to avoid long holds in cold chain."
      },
      {
        "step": "Fallback and recovery",
        "action": "If inbound raspberries arrive within 1-2 days, reduce/stop expedited buys and rebalance DC slots back to baseline; if uplift does not materialize after 48 hours, scale back allocation to avoid spoilage."
      }
    ],
    "quantitative_guidelines": {
      "dc_commitment_limit": "Do not exceed available marginal DC capacity; net DC utilization post-reallocation must remain <= 100%. Given 92% baseline utilization, allow up to ~6-7% marginal shift without additional capacity (estimate: cover ~6-9% of typical berry throughput).",
      "expedite_budget_rule": "Cap expedite spend to expected incremental gross margin (estimated uplift dollars * margin rate) for priority cohort; if unknown, set expedite cap to 25-40% of expected incremental revenue to retain profitability.",
      "priority_coverage_target": "Aim to cover 60-80% of estimated incremental demand in the top priority cohort via DC reallocation + expedited top-up; accept lower coverage (20-40%) for lower-priority Southwest stores."
    }
  },
  "opportunity_costs": [
    "Displacing other refrigerated assortments: increased stockouts or lost sales and spoilage for non-berry perishables if cold-chain capacity is rerouted.",
    "Expedite spend: higher transportation cost reduces margin and may outweigh incremental profit if uplift is weaker than forecast.",
    "Left-shift risk: committing capacity to Southwest may reduce responsiveness elsewhere if a concurrent need arises.",
    "Spoilage risk if uplift fails to materialize: over-allocation leads to markdowns/waste and full cost recognition.",
    "Reputational risk if service is uneven: prioritizing certain stores may negatively impact customers in deprioritized locations."
  ],
  "constraints": {
    "hard_constraints": [
      "DC cold-chain cannot exceed 100% utilization.",
      "Inbound raspberries have current 2-day delay; cannot be relied on for day-0 availability.",
      "Perishable shelf-life limits holding time—excess inventory cannot be stored beyond freshness window."
    ],
    "soft_constraints": [
      "Corporate service-level targets and regional fairness guidelines (avoid long-term biased deprioritization).",
      "Budget cap for expedited logistics and emergency buys.",
      "Store-level labor/handling capacity for increased delivery cadence."
    ]
  },
  "human_review_required": true,
  "review_questions": [
    "Demand validation: What is the confidence interval for the 18% Southwest uplift? Provide store-level forecast distributions vs baseline, adjusted for last year’s stockout censoring.",
    "Supply confirmation: What exact incremental marginal cold-chain capacity can be freed without violating other SLAs? Provide DC slot-by-slot impact and candidate SKUs to defer.",
    "Inbound status: Can inbound raspberries be re-routed or expedited from current carrier? What is the updated ETA and minimum guaranteed quantities?",
    "Financial guardrails: What is the maximum expedite spend acceptable (absolute $ and percent of expected incremental margin) before ROI turns negative?",
    "Prioritization criteria: Do regional merchandising and store ops agree with the proposed priority cohort and the 60-80% coverage target for those stores?",
    "Operational feasibility: Can store labor/receiving handle increased delivery cadence and smaller, more frequent picks for the 6-day window?",
